var Global_CCS_PensionRule_38 = [

    ['Which of the following is/are correct? \n1. A Government servant who was dismissed, removed or compulsorily retired from service, and is subsequently reinstated on appeal or review, is entitled to count his past service as qualifying service. \n2. The period of interruption in service between the date of dismissal or removal and the date of reinstatement shall count as qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 25- Counting of past service on reinstatement- \n(1) A Government servant who was dismissed, removed or compulsorily retired from service, and is subsequently reinstated on appeal or review, is entitled to count his past service as qualifying service. \n(2) The period of interruption in service between the date of dismissal, removal or compulsory retirement, as the case may be, and the date of reinstatement, and the period of suspension, if any, shall not count as qualifying service unless regularized as duty or leave by a specific order of the authority which passed the order of reinstatement.'],
['What are the conditions for a government servant to withdraw their resignation in the public interest?','The resignation was tendered for compelling reasons that did not reflect on the person\'s integrity, efficiency, or conduct and the request to withdraw the resignation is due to a material change in circumstances.','The person\'s conduct during the period between the resignation becoming effective and the request to withdraw is not improper and the post vacated by the person or a comparable post is available.','The period of absence from duty between the resignation becoming effective and the request to withdraw is no more than 90 days.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 26(5)- The appointing authority may permit a person to withdraw his resignation in the public interest on the following conditions, namely :- \n(i) that the resignation was tendered by the Government servant for some compelling reasons which did not involve any reflection on his integrity, efficiency or conduct and the request for withdrawal of the resignation has been made as a result of a material change in the circumstances which originally compelled him to tender the resignation; \n(ii) that during the period intervening between the date on which the resignation became effective and the date from which the request for withdrawal was made, the conduct of the person concerned was in no way improper; \n(iii) that the period of absence from duty between the date on which the resignation became effective and the date on which the person applies for permission to withdraw the resignation is not more than ninety days; \n(iv) that the post, which was vacated by the Government servant on the acceptance of his resignation or any other comparable post, is available.'],
['Appointing authority cannot accept request for withdrawal of resignation in certain cases. These case(s) include:','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a private commercial company.','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a corporation or company owned or controlled by the government','resignation with the intention of taking up a job in a body controlled or financed by the government.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 26(6): Request for withdrawal of a resignation shall not be accepted by the appointing authority where a Government servant resigns his service or post with a view to taking up an appointment in or under a private commercial company or in or under a corporation or company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Government or in or under a body controlled or financed by the Government.'],
['When an order is passed by the appointing authority allowing a person to withdraw his resignation and to resume duty, then: \n1. The order shall be deemed to include the condonation of interruption in service. \n2. The period of such interruption shall count as qualifying service.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 26(7) When an order is passed by the appointing authority allowing a person to withdraw his resignation and to resume duty, the order shall be deemed to include the condonation of interruption in service but the period of interruption shall not count as qualifying service.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. Resignation does not result in forfeiture of past service if it is taken up with permission to another position under the government. \n2. Leave or formal condonation will cover interruptions in service due to two appointments at different stations, as long as the period does not exceed the permitted joining time under transfer rules.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 26(1): Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \nrule 26(2) A resignation shall not entail forfeiture of past service if it has been submitted to take up, with proper permission, another appointment, whether temporary or permanent, under the Government where service qualifies. \nRule 26(3) The order accepting the resignation should clearly indicate that the Government servant has resigned to join another appointment with proper permission and a specific entry to this effect shall also be made by the Head of Office in the service book of the Government servant. \nRule 26(4) Interruption in service in a case falling under sub-rule (2), due to the two appointments being at different stations, not exceeding the joining time permissible under the rules of transfer, shall be covered by grant of leave of any kind due to the Government servant on the date of relief or by formal condonation to the extent to which the period is not covered by leave due to him.'],
['Which of the following circumstances would result in forfeiture of a government servant\'s past service?','Suspension followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension.','Unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence until the post of absentee is not filled substantively.','Transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government, ordered by a competent authority in the public interest.','Resignation from a service or a post.','Resignation from a service or a post.','Rule 26- Forfeiture of service on resignation.- (1) Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \n Rule 27(1) An interruption in the service of a Government servant entails forfeiture of his past service, except in the following cases, namely:- \n(a) authorised leave of absence; \n(b) unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence so long as the post of absentee is not filled substantively; \n(c) suspension, where it is immediately followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the Government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension; \n(d) transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government if such transfer has been ordered by a competent authority in the public interest; \n(e) joining time while on transfer from one post to another. \nRule 27(2) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), the appointing authority may, by order, commute retrospectively the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave.'],
['Select the correct code from below: \n1. The appointing authority may commute the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave. \n2. if a Government servant is absent without authorization after his authorized leave period has ended, but the post he was occupying has not been filled, his past service will be forfeited if such absence exceeds 180 days.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 26- Forfeiture of service on resignation.- (1) Resignation from a service or a post, unless it is allowed to be withdrawn in the public interest by the appointing authority, entails forfeiture of past service. \n Rule 27(1) An interruption in the service of a Government servant entails forfeiture of his past service, except in the following cases, namely:- \n(a) authorised leave of absence; \n(b) unauthorised absence in continuation of authorized leave of absence so long as the post of absentee is not filled substantively; \n(c) suspension, where it is immediately followed by reinstatement, whether in the same or a different post, or where the Government servant dies or is permitted to retire or is retired on attaining the age of superannuation while under suspension; \n(d) transfer to non-qualifying service in an establishment under the control of the Government if such transfer has been ordered by a competent authority in the public interest; \n(e) joining time while on transfer from one post to another. \nRule 27(2) Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), the appointing authority may, by order, commute retrospectively the periods of absence without leave as extraordinary leave.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. If there is no mention in the service book, any gap between two spells of civil service rendered by a government servant will be automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service will be considered as qualifying service. \n2. This does not apply to civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates under the government.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service- \n(1) In the absence of a specific indication to the contrary in the service book, an interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant under Government including civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service treated as qualifying service.'],
['Interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service as qualifying service except in which of the following case(s):','Resignation','Removal from Service or Dismissal','For participation in a strike','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service- \n(1) In the absence of a specific indication to the contrary in the service book, an interruption between two spells of civil service rendered by a Government servant under Government including civil service rendered and paid out of Defence Services Estimates or Railway Estimates shall be treated as automatically condoned and the pre-interruption service treated as qualifying service. \n(2) Nothing in sub-rule (1) shall apply to interruption caused by resignation, dismissal or removal from service or for participation in a strike.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct: \n1. Interruption between two spells of civil service is automatically condoned if not indicated otherwise in service book and exceptions include interruptions due to resignation, dismissal, removal from service, or participation in a strike. \n2. The appointing authority may consider condonation and treat the interruption period as qualifying. \n3. Appointing authority may refuse condonation in exceptional and grave circumstances, but the government servant must be given a chance to be heard before the decision.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','2 and 3 only','All of the above','1 and 3 only','Rule 28- Condonation of interruption in service: \nInterruption between two spells of civil service is automatically condoned if not indicated otherwise in the service book. \nExceptions include interruptions due to resignation, dismissal, removal from service, or participation in a strike.\nThe interrupted period does not count as qualifying service. \nThe appointing authority may consider condonation and treat the pre-interruption service as qualifying. \nThe appointing authority may decline condonation in exceptional and grave circumstances.\n The government servant must be given a reasonable opportunity to be heard before any decision is made against condonation.'],
['Can a Government servant count their foreign service to UN bodies as qualifying for pension if they do not pay pension contributions for it?','Yes','No','Only if they are deputed to the United Nations Secretariat','Only if they are deputed to the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development.','No','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['If a Government servant opts not to pay pension contributions for their foreign service in International Organization, what happens to the contributions, if any, already paid by the Government servant?','They are used to fund other pension schemes.','They are refunded to the Govt. Servant','They are paid to the Govt. Servant on their return from such service.','None of the above','They are refunded to the Govt. Servant','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['Which of the following options is available to a Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to Asian Development Bank?','To pay pension contributions in respect of foreign service and count it as qualifying for pension under these rules.','To not pay pension contributions in respect of foreign service and not count it as qualifying for pension under these rules.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 29: A Government servant who is deputed on foreign service to the United Nations Secretariat or other UN bodies or the International Monetary Fund or the International Bank of Reconstruction and Development, or the Asian Development Bank or the Commonwealth Secretariat or any other International organization may opt,- (a) to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules; or (b) not to pay the pension contributions in respect of his foreign service and not count such service as qualifying for pension under these rules: Provided that where a Government servant opts for clause (b), pension contributions, if any, paid by the Government servant, shall be refunded to him.'],
['The ______________, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation.','Head of Department','Head of Office','Drawing and Disbursing Officer','Internal Audit Wing','Head of Office','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on which of the following occasions? \n1. After completing 18 years of service. \n2. When there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \n3. After completing 25 years of service.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','1 and 2 only','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['In the context of Pension Rules, what is the purpose of Format 4?','It indicates the period counted as non-qualifying.','To communicate to the Government servant the period of qualifying service determined.','It is the Indemnity Bond to be furnished by a claimant of Gratuity or Family Pension.','It is an Indemnity Bond by Guardian for payment of gratuity to minor.','To communicate to the Government servant the period of qualifying service determined.','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service- (1) On each occasion after a Government servant has completed eighteen years of service and on his being left with five years of service before the date of superannuation, the Head of Office in consultation with Accounts Officer shall, in accordance with the rules for the time being in force, verify the service rendered by such a Government servant, determine the qualifying service and communicate to him, in Format 4, the period of qualifying service so determined'],
['The Head of Office shall follow the procedure provided in clause (a) of sub-rule (1) of _________ for the verification of service in consultation with Accounts Officer.','Rule 56','Rule 57','Rule 58','Rule 59','Rule 57','Rule 30: The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. The Head of Office shall follow the procedure provided in clause (a) of sub-rule (1) of rule 57 for the verification of service.'],
['Under which of the following circumstance(s), the verification of service may be done: ','When a Government servant is transferred to another department from a temporary department.',' On account of the closure of the department he had been previously serving.','If the post he held had been declared surplus.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(3): Notwithstanding anything contained in sub-rule (1), where a Government servant is transferred to another department from a temporary department or on account of the closure of the department he had been previously serving or because the post he held had been declared surplus, the verification of his service may be done whenever such event occurs. '],
['In what circumstances can the verification of service be reopened under the Pension Rules?','In case of foreign service to Internationa Organization like IMF, World Bank etc.','On the request of the Govt. Servant citing valid grounds for such reverification.','When necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.','All of the above','When necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(4) The verification done under this rule shall be treated as final and shall not be reopened except when necessitated by a subsequent change in the rules and orders governing the conditions under which the service qualifies for pension.'],
['A report must be submitted to the Secretary of the Administrative Ministry or Department by ______________ every year containing details of government servants who needed a certificate of qualifying service during the previous year, those who were issued with the certificate, and the reasons why the certificate was not issued in the remaining cases.','January 31st','March 31st','September 30th','June 30th','January 31st','Rule 30- Periodic verification of qualifying service: (1)The Head of Office, in consultation with Accounts Officer, will verify the service of a Government servant on two occasions: after completing 18 years of service and when there are only 5 years left before the date of superannuation. \nRule 30(5) By 31st January of each year, a report shall be submitted to the Secretary of the Administrative Ministry or Department giving the details of the Government servants who were required to be issued a certificate of qualifying service during the previous calendar year under sub-rule (1), the details of the Government servants who have actually been issued the said certificate during the said period and the reasons for not issuing the said certificate in the remaining cases.'],
['In the context of emoluments for retirement benefits, which of the following does NOT form part of a Government servant\'s emoluments?','Basic pay as defined in Fundamental Rules, 1922','Non-practising allowance granted to a medical officer in lieu of private practice','Stagnation increment','Any increase in pay that is not actually drawn except in special case.','Any increase in pay that is not actually drawn except in special case.','Rule 31- Emoluments: \nThe term \'emoluments\' refers to a Government servant\'s basic pay at the time of retirement or death, including non-practising allowance given to medical officers in lieu of private practice. Stagnation increment will also be considered as emoluments for retirement benefits. If a Government servant was on leave or suspended before retirement or death, the emoluments he would have received if he had not been absent or suspended will be included. Any increase in pay that was not actually received will not be considered as emoluments [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (5) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (10) or sub-rule (11)].'],
['Which of the following is/are NOT correct: \n1. If a government servant was on leave (including EOL on medical certificate) immediately before his retirement or death, the emoluments he would have drawn if he were not absent would be considered for calculating retirement benefits. \n2. Increment earned but not drawn during leave before retirement or death shall be part of emoluments.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Rule 31(2): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on extraordinary leave on medical certificate or, having been suspended, had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall form part of his emoluments. \nRule 31(5) Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service, was on leave, and earned an increment which was not withheld, such increment, though not actually drawn, shall form part of his emoluments.'],
['Under what condition the benefit of emoluments is given to a Government servant who proceeds on leave after holding a higher appointment in an officiating or temporary capacity before retirement or death while in service?','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given without any condition.','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if the government servant has completed a minimum tenure in that position.','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if it is certified that the government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for the leave.','No benefit is applicable to the government servant in such cases and retirement benefits are ','The benefit of emoluments drawn in the higher appointment is given only if it is certified that the government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for the leave.','Rule 31(3): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had proceeded on leave for which leave salary is payable after having held a higher appointment whether in an officiating or temporary capacity, the benefit of emoluments drawn in such higher appointment shall be given only if it is certified that the Government servant would have continued to hold the higher appointment but for his proceeding on leave.'],
['Which of the following applies to a Government servant who had been under suspension immediately before his retirement or death while in service?','The emoluments earned during the period of suspension are included in his retirement benefits.','The emoluments earned immediately before being placed under suspension will be considered part of their total emoluments for retirement benefits.','The Government servant is not eligible for any retirement benefits.','None of the above','The emoluments earned immediately before being placed under suspension will be considered part of their total emoluments for retirement benefits.','Rule 31(4): Where a Government servant immediately before his retirement or death while in service had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave or had been under suspension, the period whereof does not count as service, the emoluments which he drew immediately before proceeding on such leave or being placed under suspension shall form part of his emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding pay drawn by a government servant while on deputation to an ex-cadre post in the same or some other department of the government or to the Armed Forces of India?','The pay received by a government servant while on such deputation will not be considered as emoluments.','if the government servant goes on leave after the completion of the deputation period, the pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments.','The pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments during the whole period of deputation','None of the above ','if the government servant goes on leave after the completion of the deputation period, the pay they would have received in their parent department will be considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(6): Pay drawn by a Government servant while on deputation to an ex-cadre post in the same or some other Department of the Government or to the Armed Forces of India shall be treated as emoluments: Provided that in the case of a Government servant while on leave after release from the ex-cadre post on completion of the period of deputation, the pay which he would have drawn in the parent department had he not been on leave shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statement is true regarding the pay of a government servant on deputation to a state government or foreign service?','The pay drawn by the government servant on such deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating retirement benefits.','The pay that the Govt. Servant would have earned if they had not been on deputation will be considered as emoluments.','It depends on the option exercised by the Govt. Servant.','The Terms & Conditions of such deputation will regulate and define the emoluments.','The pay that the Govt. Servant would have earned if they had not been on deputation will be considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(7): Pay drawn by a Government servant while on deputation to a State Government or while on foreign service shall not be treated as emoluments, but the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deputation to the State Government or on foreign service shall alone be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the treatment of emoluments for pensioners who are re-employed in government service and opt to retain their pension from earlier service?','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is not considered as emoluments.','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is considered as emoluments.','The emoluments drawn during the earlier service are not taken into account for pension calculation.','None of the above','The element of pension by which his pay is reduced is considered as emoluments.','Rule 31(8): Where a pensioner who is re-employed in Government service elected to retain his pension for earlier service and whose pay on re-employment had been reduced by an amount not exceeding his pension, the element of pension by which his pay is reduced shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding the treatment of emoluments for government servants transferred to a public sector undertaking or autonomous body after the conversion of their department?','The emoluments drawn under the new organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','The emoluments drawn under the previous organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','The employee\'s pension benefits will be forfeited upon transfer to the new organization.','None of the above','The emoluments drawn under the previous organization will be considered for pension benefits if the employee opts to retain their pension benefits.','Rule 31(9) When a Government servant has been transferred to a public sector undertaking or an autonomous body consequent on the conversion of a Department of the Government into such public sector undertaking or autonomous body and the Government servant so transferred opts to retain the pensionary benefits under the rules of the Government, the emoluments drawn under the public sector undertaking or autonomous body shall be treated as emoluments.'],
['In what circumstance will the notional pay be treated as emoluments for a retired government servant?','When the pay scale of the employee\'s previous post is increased retrospectively irrespective of the date when they were in service.',' When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)',' When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','Rule 31(10): The treatment of notional pay as emoluments for government servants who have retired but whose pay is notionally increased with retrospective effect. This includes two scenarios: \n(i) when the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively, and the pensioner\'s pay in the higher pay scale is fixed on a notional basis; \n(ii) when the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.'],
['What are the conditions for the treatment of increased notional pay as emoluments for a retired government servant? \n1. When the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order. \n2. The benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 31(10): The treatment of notional pay as emoluments for government servants who have retired but whose pay is notionally increased with retrospective effect. This includes two scenarios: \n(i) when the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively, and the pensioner\'s pay in the higher pay scale is fixed on a notional basis; \n(ii) when the retired government servant is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a Review DPC or due to exoneration in departmental proceedings or court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed to the pensioner on a notional basis from the date of promotion.'],
['What happens when a Govt. servant dies during the currency of the penalty that reduces their pay only until the expiry of the penalty?','The penalty will continue to affect the government servant\'s pay even after their death.','The notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty are treated as emoluments.','The order imposing the said penalty will have specific mention in this regard.','None of the above','The notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty are treated as emoluments.','Rule 31(11): Where a Government servant dies during the currency of a penalty which has the effect of reducing his pay only during the currency of that penalty and on expiry of which he would have regained the pay admissible to him without any impact of the said penalty, the notional pay on the date of death ignoring the effect of such penalty shall be treated as emoluments'],
['Average emoluments shall be determined with reference to the emoluments drawn by a Government servant during the last ___________________ of his service.','Six months','Ten months','Twelve months','Eighteen months','Ten months','Rule 32: Average emoluments shall be determined with reference to the emoluments drawn by a Government servant during the last ten months of his service.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the calculation of average emoluments for a government servant who is absent from duty for which leave salary is payable or suspended (followed by reinstatement) during the last ten months of their service?','The emoluments they actually receive during this time will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The emoluments they would have received if they were not absent or suspended will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Any increase in pay during this time will be included in their emoluments, even if it was not actually received.','None of the above','The emoluments they would have received if they were not absent or suspended will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Rule 32(2): In case during the last ten months of his service a Government servant had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate or having been suspended had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments : \nProvided that any increase in pay [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (4) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (5) or sub-rule (6)] which is not actually drawn shall not form part of his emoluments.'],
['The average emoluments in respect of a Govt. Servant who is on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate during the last 10 months of service will be :','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','None of the above','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','Rule 32(2): In case during the last ten months of his service a Government servant had been absent from duty on leave for which leave salary is payable or on Extraordinary leave on medical certificate or having been suspended had been reinstated without forfeiture of service, the emoluments which he would have drawn had he not been absent from duty or suspended shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments : \nProvided that any increase in pay [other than the increment referred to in sub-rule (4) and the notional increase in pay referred to in sub-rule (5) or sub-rule (6)] which is not actually drawn shall not form part of his emoluments.'],
['The average emoluments in respect of a Govt. Servant who is on Extraordinary leave during the last 10 months of service will be :','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not on EOL (on MC) will be used to determine their average emoluments.','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','None of the above','The period of EOL will be disregarded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten months will be included.','Rule 32(3): In case during the last ten months of his service, a Government servant had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave, or had been under suspension the period whereof does not count as service, the aforesaid period of leave or suspension shall be disregarded in the calculation of the average emoluments and equal period before the ten months shall be included. In order that the fractions of a month, when added, worked out to one full month, a month for this purpose shall be reckoned as consisting of thirty days. \nIllustration: A Government servant retires on 16th July, 2019. The last ten months comprise nine full months and fractions of fourteen days of September, 2018 and sixteen days of July, 2019. The emoluments for fractional periods shall be computed by multiplying the emolument by the factor 14/30 and 16/30 irrespective of the number of days in the month. This formula shall also apply in the case of the month of February, irrespective of whether the month has twenty eight days or twenty nine days.'],
['If a Government servant was under suspension during the last ten months of their service, and if this period does not count towards their service then the Average emoluments will be:','Zero','The emoluments they would have received if they were not under suspension will be used to determine their average emoluments.','the period of suspension will be excluded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten-month period will be included in the calculation','None of the above','the period of suspension will be excluded when calculating their average emoluments and an equal period of time before the ten-month period will be included in the calculation','Rule 32(3): In case during the last ten months of his service, a Government servant had been absent from duty on extraordinary leave, or had been under suspension the period whereof does not count as service, the aforesaid period of leave or suspension shall be disregarded in the calculation of the average emoluments and equal period before the ten months shall be included. In order that the fractions of a month, when added, worked out to one full month, a month for this purpose shall be reckoned as consisting of thirty days. \nIllustration: A Government servant retires on 16th July, 2019. The last ten months comprise nine full months and fractions of fourteen days of September, 2018 and sixteen days of July, 2019. The emoluments for fractional periods shall be computed by multiplying the emolument by the factor 14/30 and 16/30 irrespective of the number of days in the month. This formula shall also apply in the case of the month of February, irrespective of whether the month has twenty eight days or twenty nine days.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the inclusion of increments in the average emoluments for pension calculations?','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is not included','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is included, even if it was not actually received','Only increments earned during active service are included','None of the above','An increment earned during leave in the last ten months of service is included, even if it was not actually received','Rule 32(4): (4) In the case of a Government servant who was on leave during the last ten months of his service and earned an increment, which was not withheld, such increment though not actually drawn shall be included in the average emoluments.'],
['When is the notional pay increase of a Government servant, with retrospective effect during the last ten months of their service after retirement, taken into account for calculating their average emoluments?','if the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively.','if the pensioner is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a review Departmental Promotion Committee, or on exoneration in any departmental proceedings, or in compliance with a court order.','if the benefit of pay fixation is allowed on a notional basis from the date of such promotion.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 32(4): If a Government servant was on leave during the last ten months of their service and earned an increment, which was not withheld, then the increment will be included in the average emoluments even if it was not actually received. \nRule 32(5): If the pay of a Government servant is increased with retrospective effect during the last ten months of their service after retirement, then the notional pay will be taken into account for determining the average emoluments. This applies if the pay scale of the post from which the pensioner retired is increased retrospectively or if the pensioner is promoted retrospectively on the recommendation of a review Departmental Promotion Committee, or on exoneration in any departmental proceedings, or in compliance with a court order, and the benefit of pay fixation is allowed on a notional basis from the date of such promotion.'],
['What happens to average emoluments when a Govt. servant dies during the currency of the penalty that reduces their pay only until the expiry of the penalty?','The penalty will continue to affect the government servant\'s average emoluments even after their death.','The notional pay during the last ten months of service, without the impact of the penalty, will be considered for calculating their average emoluments.','The order imposing the said penalty will have specific mention in this regard.','None of the above','The notional pay during the last ten months of service, without the impact of the penalty, will be considered for calculating their average emoluments.','Rule 32(6): Where a Government servant dies during the currency of a penalty which has the effect of reducing his pay only during the currency of that penalty and on expiry of which he would have regained the pay admissible to him without any impact of the said penalty, the notional pay during the last ten months of his service ignoring the effect of such penalty shall be taken into account for determining the average emoluments.'],
['When a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation, they shall be granted a superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as per the provisions of _______________.','Rule 42','Rule 43','Rule 44','Rule 45','Rule 44','Rule 33- Superannuation pension or service gratuity.- A superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as the case may be, shall be granted in accordance with rule 44 to a Government servant who is retired on his attaining the age of superannuation or, if the service of the Government servant has been extended beyond superannuation, on expiry of such period of extension of service beyond the age of superannuation.'],
['Which of the following is true about the grant of superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity to a Government servant?','It is only granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation','It is only granted when a Government servant\'s service is extended beyond the age of superannuation.','It is granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation','None of the above','It is granted when a Government servant attains the age of superannuation or when their service is extended beyond the age of superannuation','Rule 33- Superannuation pension or service gratuity.- A superannuation pension or superannuation service gratuity, as the case may be, shall be granted in accordance with rule 44 to a Government servant who is retired on his attaining the age of superannuation or, if the service of the Government servant has been extended beyond superannuation, on expiry of such period of extension of service beyond the age of superannuation.'],
['A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee: \n1. who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of Fundamental Rule or rule 56 of CCS Pension Rules, 2021. \n2. who is retired by the Government, before attaining the age of superannuation, in accordance with the provisions of rule 42 of these rules or rule 56 of the Fundamental Rules. \n3. who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1, 2 and 3','None of the above','2 and 3 only','Rule 34- Retiring pension or service gratuity- A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of these rules or rule 56 of Fundamental rules. The pension or gratuity is also given to an employee who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme. The government may retire an employee before reaching the age of superannuation in accordance with rule 42 of these rules or Fundamental rule 56. The specific rules governing the awarding of the pension or gratuity are detailed in rule 44.'],
['Which of the following statements is true regarding the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme for government servants who are declared surplus?','Employees who opt for the scheme are not eligible for any retirement gratuity.','All such Govt. Servant are entitled to ex-gratia payment.','Employees who opt for the scheme are entitled to a retiring pension or service gratuity in accordance with rule 44.','The scheme is only available to employees who retire on their own volition.','Employees who opt for the scheme are entitled to a retiring pension or service gratuity in accordance with rule 44.','"Rule 34- Retiring pension or service gratuity- A retiring pension or gratuity is granted to a government employee who retires voluntarily before reaching the age of superannuation according to rule 43 of these rules or rule 56 of Fundamental rules. The pension or gratuity is also given to an employee who is declared surplus and opts for voluntary retirement according to the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme. The government may retire an employee before reaching the age of superannuation in accordance with rule 42 of these rules or Fundamental rule 56. The specific rules governing the awarding of the pension or gratuity are detailed in rule 44. \n Rule 34(2): If a permanent government servant is declared surplus to the establishment and chooses to opt for the Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme, they will be entitled to an ex-gratia payment according to the scheme. This will be in addition to the retiring pension or service gratuity awarded in accordance with rule 44, as well as the retirement gratuity under rule 45.'],
['What happens when a government servant is absorbed into a service or post in a state government?','They are not eligible for pension or gratuity.','They will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption.','They will be eligible for pension or gratuity, but not retirement gratuity.','They will be eligible for retirement gratuity, but not pension or gratuity.','They will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45: \nProvided that on retirement from the State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in the State Government shall not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in the Central Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from the State Government.'],
['What is the limit on the total amount of gratuity for a government servant who has been absorbed into a service or post in a state government?','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the state government service.','There is no limit on the total amount of gratuity.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on the same pay as they did when retiring from the state government.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on a pay which is 1 stage lower than what they received when retiring from the state government.','The total amount of gratuity for their service under both governments cannot exceed the amount that would have been given if the employee had continued in the central government service and retired on the same pay as they did when retiring from the state government.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45: \nProvided that on retirement from the State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in the State Government shall not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in the Central Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from the State Government.'],
['What is the date of absorption for a government employee who joins a state government?','The date of acceptance of their resignation from the central government service.','The date on which they submit their resignation to the central government.','The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis.','The date on which their deputation to the state government begins.','The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- \n35(1): If a government servant is allowed to be absorbed into a service or post in a state government, they will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption. They will be eligible for pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on their qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45. \n 35(2): The date of absorption for a government employee who joins a state government shall be: \n(i) The date on which they actually join the state government if they join on immediate absorption basis. Immediate absorption refers to the acceptance of a technical resignation from the central government service to take up an appointment in the state government for which they had applied with proper permission. \n(ii) The date from which their unqualified resignation is accepted by the central government if they initially join the state government on deputation.'],
['When a government employee joins the state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in _____________ indicating the period within which they must join the state government.','Format 3','Format 4','Format 5','Format 6','Format 5','Rule 35(3): When a government employee joins a state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in Format 5 indicating the period within which they must join the state government. This period can be extended by the relieving authority if there are reasons beyond the control of the government servant. \nRule 35(4): The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave or extraordinary leave.'],
['When a Government employee joins a State Government on immediate absorption, which of the following is applicable?','The relieving order will be issued in Format 7 indicating the period within which they must join the state government.','This period may be extended by the relieving authority on specific request of the Servant.','The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave due and admissible or extraordinary leave, if no leave is due.','if the joining is not within the specified period then the excess duration will be treated as interruption in service and it won\'t qualify. ','The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave due and admissible or extraordinary leave, if no leave is due.','Rule 35(3): When a government employee joins a state government on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order will be issued in Format 5 indicating the period within which they must join the state government. This period can be extended by the relieving authority if there are reasons beyond the control of the government servant. \nRule 35(4): The period between the date of relief and the date of joining the state government may be regularized by granting leave or extraordinary leave.'],
['Which of the following statement is accurate with regard to accepting the resignation of a government servant who joins a state government on immediate absorption basis?','The resignation is accepted from the same date as the date of joining the state government.','The resignation is accepted from the date preceding the date of joining the state government.','The resignation is not required to be accepted.','None of the above','The resignation is accepted from the date preceding the date of joining the state government.','Rule 35: Pension on absorption in or under a State Government- \n35(1): If a government servant is allowed to be absorbed into a service or post in a state government, they will be deemed to have retired from the central government service from the date of absorption. \nRule 35(5): The relieving authority, before processing the case for sanction of retirement benefits, will ascertain the date of joining by the Government servant in the State Government and accept the resignation of the Government servant from the date preceding the date of joining.'],
['What options are available to a Government servant who is absorbed by a State Government and a similar pension scheme exists in that State Government?','To receive only the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government.','To count only the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','To either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government or count the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','No options are applicable in this case and the Govt. Servant is deemed to have retired on such absorption.','To either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government or count the service rendered under the Central Government in the State Government.','Rule 35- Pension on absorption in or under a State Government: \nRule 35(1) A Government servant, who has been permitted to be absorbed in a service or post in or under a State Government, shall be deemed to have retired from service under the Central Government from the date of such absorption and, subject to sub-rule (6), he shall be eligible, on such absorption, to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity on the basis of the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45. \nRule 35(6) Where a pension scheme similar to the pension scheme under these rules exists in the State Government in which a Government servant is absorbed, he shall be entitled to exercise option either,- (a) to receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with sub-rule (1); or (b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government.'],
['Who bears the liability of proportionate pension when a Government servant exercises an option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in a State Government?','The Central Government will bear the liability of proportionate pension upon retirement.',' The State Government will bear the liability of proportionate pension upon retirement.','There will be no liability of proportionate pension borne by the Central Government upon retirement.','None of the above','There will be no liability of proportionate pension borne by the Central Government upon retirement.','Rule 35(6): Where a pension scheme similar to the pension scheme under these rules exists in the State Government in which a Government servant is absorbed, he shall be entitled to exercise option either,- \n(a) to receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with sub-rule (1); or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government. \nRule 35(7): When a Government servant is absorbed in a State Government and chooses to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that State Government, the State Government will be responsible for paying the pension and gratuity for the entire service, including the service rendered in the Central Government, upon retirement. The Central Government will not have any liability of proportionate pension in this case.'],
['When a Government servant is absorbed in a Corporation or Company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government, the total amount of gratuity in respect of the service rendered under the Government and the service rendered in such Corporation or Company shall not exceed:','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from that Corporation or Company.','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant retired from Government service on the same pay which he drew on the date of absorption in that Corporation or Company','Either (a) or (b) whichever is higher','None of the above','The amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay which he drew on retirement from that Corporation or Company.','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nA Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nThe total amount of gratuity on retirement from the Corporation, Company or Body, in respect of service rendered under the Government and the Corporation/Company/Body, should not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay from the Corporation/Company/Body.'],
['A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have ______________ from service from the date of absorption.','Resigned','Retired','Tecnically resigned','None of the above','Retired','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nA Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension or service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nThe total amount of gratuity on retirement from the Corporation, Company or Body, in respect of service rendered under the Government and the Corporation/Company/Body, should not exceed the amount that would have been admissible had the Government servant continued in Government service and retired on the same pay from the Corporation/Company/Body.'],
['What is the date of absorption in the case of a government employee who initially joins a corporation or company or body on foreign service terms?','The date on which he actually joins that corporation or company or body','The date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the Government','The date on which he completes his foreign service tenure.','None of the above','The date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the Government','Rule 36(2): The date of absorption for a government servant who joins a corporation or company or body wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government or in or under a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government shall be: \n(i) the date on which the government servant actually joins the corporation or company or body, if he joins on immediate absorption basis. \n ii) the date from which his unqualified resignation is accepted by the government, if he initially joins the corporation or company or body on foreign service terms.'],
['The absorption of a Govt. Servant in or under a corporation, company or body may be permitted: \n1. In or under a Corporation or Company wholly or substantially owned or controlled by the Central Government or a State Government. \n2. In or under a Body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government. \n3. In joint sector undertakings under the joint control of Central/State Governments or Union territory administrations or multiple State Governments or Union territory administrations.','1 and 2 only','2 and 3 only','1 and 3 only','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nOn absorption, the Government servant is eligible to receive pension, service gratuity, and retirement gratuity based on the qualifying service and emoluments on the date of absorption in accordance with Rule 44 and Rule 45. \nRule 36(3): The provisions of sub-rule (1) shall also apply to Central Government servants who are permitted to be absorbed in joint sector undertakings, wholly under the joint control of the Central Government and State Governments or Union territory administrations or under the joint control of two or more State Governments or Union territory administrations.'],
['Which of the following is/are correct for a Government employee joining a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption: \n1. A relieving order shall be issued in Format 4 indicating the period within which the Government servant should join. \n2. The relieving authority may extend the period if the Government servant has reasons beyond their control, which must be recorded in writing.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','2 only','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \n Rule 36(4) In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order shall be issued in the Format 5. \nRule 36(5) The relieving order shall indicate the period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body: Provided that this period may be extended by the relieving authority for reasons beyond the control of the Government servant, which shall be recorded in writing. \nRule 36(6) The period between the date of relief and the date of joining in the Corporation or Company or the Body may be regularised by grant of leave due and if no such leave is due, the period may be regularised by grant of extraordinary leave.'],
['In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, what does the relieving order issued in Format 5 indicate?','The emoluments to be received by the Government servant.','The period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body','The amount of service gratuity to be received by the Government servant','The amount of retirement gratuity to be received by the Government servant','The period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \n Rule 36(4) In the case of a Government servant who joins a corporation or company or body on immediate absorption basis, the relieving order shall be issued in the Format 5. \nRule 36(5) The relieving order shall indicate the period within which the Government servant shall join the Corporation or Company or the Body: Provided that this period may be extended by the relieving authority for reasons beyond the control of the Government servant, which shall be recorded in writing. \nRule 36(6) The period between the date of relief and the date of joining in the Corporation or Company or the Body may be regularised by grant of leave due and if no such leave is due, the period may be regularised by grant of extraordinary leave.'],
['What happens to the Government servant\'s lien in the relieving department upon absorption in the Corporation or Company or Body?','It is retained by the Government servant for 2 years from the date of absorption','It is transferred to the Corporation or Company or Body','It is terminated and all connections with the Government are severed','It is suspended until the Government servant\'s return to Government service','It is terminated and all connections with the Government are severed','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(8) No lien of the Government servant shall be retained in the relieving department and all his connections with the Government shall stand severed on his absorption in the Corporation or Company or the Body.'],
['Which of the following options is available to a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government where a similar pension scheme exists?','To receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government','To count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension','Either (a) or (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Either (a) or (b)','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension.'],
['What happens when a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government exercises an option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body?','The Government will continue to pay the pension as usual.','The Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one-time payment.','The Government will transfer the pension liability to the body.','There is no pension liability on Central Govt. in such case','The Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one-time payment.','Rule 36- Pension on absorption in or under a corporation, company or body: \nRule 36(1): A Government servant who is absorbed in a Corporation, Company or Body owned or controlled by Central/State Government is deemed to have retired from service from the date of absorption. \nRule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10) Where a Government servant is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government and exercises an option under clause (b) of sub-rule (9), the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying in lump sum as a one time payment.'],
['How is the lump sum amount of pension determined in the case of a Government servant absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central Government or a State Government?','Based on the last drawn salary of the Government servant.','Based on the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.','Based on the Contributory Provident Fund Rules (India ), 1962','Based on the number of years of service rendered by the Government servant.','Based on the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.','Rule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10): if a Government servant chooses option (b) under sub-rule (9) and is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government, the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying a lump sum as a one-time payment. \nRule 36(11): The pension liability will comprise the capitalized value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body. \nRule 36(12): The amount of the lump sum pension will be determined using the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],
['What does the pension liability comprise of for a government servant who is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government?','Only the capitalised value of pension.','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of relieving from Central Govt.','Only the capitalised value of service gratuity and retirement gratuity up to the date of relieving from Central Govt.','The capitalised value of pension, service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body','Rule 36(9): If a government servant is absorbed into a body controlled or financed by the Central or State Government, and if a pension scheme similar to the one under these rules exists in that body, the government servant has the option to either receive retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Central Government, or count the service rendered in that body for pension. \nRule 36(10): if a Government servant chooses option (b) under sub-rule (9) and is absorbed in a body controlled or financed by the Central/State Government, the Government will discharge its pension liability by paying a lump sum as a one-time payment. \nRule 36(11): The pension liability will comprise the capitalized value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service up to the date of absorption in that body. \nRule 36(12): The amount of the lump sum pension will be determined using the Table of values for commutation of pension appended to the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.'],
['What is the time frame within which a public sector undertaking must frame its rules and regulations after the conversion of a Central Government department?','Not exceeding five years','Not exceeding two years','Not exceeding three years','Not exceeding four years','Not exceeding five years','Rule 37- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking: \n In case of a department of the Central Government being converted into a public sector undertaking, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking, on deemed deputation on foreign service terms without any deputation allowance until they get absorbed in the said undertaking. The public sector undertaking shall frame its rules and regulations within five years, and after that, the Government servants on deemed deputation shall be asked to exercise their option to revert back to the Government or seek permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking within three months. The option shall be exercised in the manner specified by the Government.'],
['Within what time period must Government servants on deemed deputation exercise their option to revert back to the Government or seek permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking, after the public sector undertaking has notified its rules and regulations?','Not exceeding six months','Not exceeding three months','Not exceeding twelve months','Not exceeding 1 mont month','Not exceeding three months','Rule 37- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking: \n In case of a department of the Central Government being converted into a public sector undertaking, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking, on deemed deputation on foreign service terms without any deputation allowance until they get absorbed in the said undertaking. The public sector undertaking shall frame its rules and regulations within five years, and after that, the Government servants on deemed deputation shall be asked to exercise their option to revert back to the Government or seek permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking within three months. The option shall be exercised in the manner specified by the Government.'],
['In the context of the conversion of a department of the Central Government into a public sector undertaking, which of the following is correct? \n1. In such cases, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking. \n2. It will be treated as deemed deputation on terms of foreign service with deputation allowance till such time as they get absorbed in the said undertaking. ','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','1 only','Rule 37- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking: \n In case of a department of the Central Government being converted into a public sector undertaking, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking, on deemed deputation on foreign service terms without any deputation allowance until they get absorbed in the said undertaking. The public sector undertaking shall frame its rules and regulations within five years, and after that, the Government servants on deemed deputation shall be asked to exercise their option to revert back to the Government or seek permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking within three months. The option shall be exercised in the manner specified by the Government.'],
['When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking and the employees have three months to decide (after framing of rules) whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. In this context, which of the following is NOT correct?','if a Government servant does not exercise any option within the prescribed time limit, he/she will be deemed to have opted for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking.','The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which they excercise their options.','Upon absorption, the posts which the employees were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished.','If employees opt to revert to Government service, they shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government.','The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which they excercise their options.','The Rule 37 relates to Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking.\n The summary of Rule 37(1) to 37(8) is as under:\n When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are transferred en-masse on deemed deputation without deputation allowance until absorbed by the undertaking. The undertaking must frame its rules within five years. After that, the employees have three months to decide whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. if a Government servant does not exercise any option within the prescribed time limit, he/she will be deemed to have opted for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking. The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which their options are accepted by the Government. Upon absorption, the posts which the employees were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished. If employees opt to revert to Government service, they shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government. The period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.'],
['When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking and the employee opts to revert back to Govt, how does the period between the date of option and the date of reversion is treated?','The period is considered as a interruption in service for the Government servants.','The period is considered as deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.','The period is considered as deemed deputation on terms of foreign service with entitlement to deputation allowance.','The period is treated as if the Govt. Servant has reverted back to the Govt. until formal order to this effect are issued.','The period is considered as deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.','The Rule 37 relates to Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking.\n The summary of Rule 37(1) to 37(8) is as under:\n When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are transferred en-masse on deemed deputation without deputation allowance until absorbed by the undertaking. The undertaking must frame its rules within five years. After that, the employees have three months to decide whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. if a Government servant does not exercise any option within the prescribed time limit, he/she will be deemed to have opted for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking. The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which their options are accepted by the Government. Upon absorption, the posts which the employees were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished. If employees opt to revert to Government service, they shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government. The period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.'],
['What is the timeline within which employees who opt to revert to Government service must be repatriated after a Central Government department is converted into a public sector undertaking?','Within 3 months from the date of exercise of the option','Within 6 months from the date of exercise of the option','Within one year from the date of exercise of the option','Within two years from the date of exercise of the option','Within two years from the date of exercise of the option','The Rule 37 relates to Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking.\n The summary of Rule 37(1) to 37(8) is as under:\n When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are transferred en-masse on deemed deputation without deputation allowance until absorbed by the undertaking. The undertaking must frame its rules within five years. After that, the employees have three months to decide whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. if a Government servant does not exercise any option within the prescribed time limit, he/she will be deemed to have opted for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking. The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which their options are accepted by the Government. Upon absorption, the posts which the employees were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished. If employees opt to revert to Government service, they shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government. The period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.'],
['When a Central Government department is converted into a public sector undertaking, the employees have the option to either get absorbed or revert back to the government service. If they choose to get absorbed in the public sector undertaking, the posts that they were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand _________________.','deemed abolished','abolished','in suspended animation unitl revived with the approval of D/o Expenditure','None of the above','abolished','The Rule 37 relates to Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking.\n The summary of Rule 37(1) to 37(8) is as under:\n When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are transferred en-masse on deemed deputation without deputation allowance until absorbed by the undertaking. The undertaking must frame its rules within five years. After that, the employees have three months to decide whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. if a Government servant does not exercise any option within the prescribed time limit, he/she will be deemed to have opted for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking. The permanent absorption will take effect from the date on which their options are accepted by the Government. Upon absorption, the posts which the employees were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished. If employees opt to revert to Government service, they shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government. The period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.'],
['When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are treated as on deemed deputation on foreign service terms. What happens to the pensionary benefits of an employee who dies or retires during this period?','Pensionary benefits will be calculated based on the pay they would have received under the Central Government if they had not been on deemed deputation','Pensionary benefits will be calculated based on the pay they were receiving under the Public Sector Undertaking','The pay on which Pensionary benefits will be specified by the concerned Administrative Ministry/Department.','It will be governed by the rules framed by the D/o Public Enterprises in force at that time. ','Pensionary benefits will be calculated based on the pay they would have received under the Central Government if they had not been on deemed deputation','Rule 37- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking: \n In case of a department of the Central Government being converted into a public sector undertaking, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking, on deemed deputation on foreign service terms without any deputation allowance until they get absorbed in the said undertaking. \nRule 37(9): Where an employee retires or dies during the period of such deemed deputation, the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government. \nRule 37(10) The pensionary benefits in respect of such employee shall be drawn and paid in the manner to be specified by the administrative Ministry of the public sector undertaking.'],
['When a Central Government department becomes a public sector undertaking, its employees are treated as on deemed deputation and they have the option to decide whether to revert back to the Government or be permanently absorbed in the undertaking. In this regard, employees who opt for permanent absorption in a public sector undertaking, will be governed by the rules and regulations or bye-laws of the undertaking from the date of absorption, excluding __________________.','temporary employees only','casual labourers only','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','casual labourers only','Rule 37- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking: \n In case of a department of the Central Government being converted into a public sector undertaking, all Government servants of that department shall be transferred en-masse to that public sector undertaking, on deemed deputation on foreign service terms without any deputation allowance until they get absorbed in the said undertaking. \nRule 37(11) Employees, excluding casual labourers, who opt for permanent absorption in the public sector undertaking will be governed by the rules and regulations or bye-laws of the undertaking from the date of absorption, subject to the provisions of sub-rule (12) to sub-rule (17).'],
['A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a public sector undertaking is entitled to exercise which of the following options? \n1. To receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity from the Government for the service rendered under the Central Government. \n2. To count the service rendered under the Central Government in that PSU for pension and gratuity.','1 only','2 only','Either 1 or 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Either 1 or 2','Rule 37(12): A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a public sector undertaking shall be entitled to exercise option either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity from the Government for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45; or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that public sector undertaking for pension and gratuity.'],
['Two options available to a Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a PSU. They can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. In the case of a Government servant who has exercised option (a), what shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government?','The pay which he is currently drawing under the public sector undertaking.','The pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation','It is decided by the guidelines of D/o Public Enterprises and no options as such is available in this case. ','None of the above','The pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation','Rule 37(12): A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a public sector undertaking shall be entitled to exercise option either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity from the Government for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45; or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that public sector undertaking for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(13): (13) In the case of a Government servant who has exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (12), the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government and the pensionary benefits in respect of such employee shall be drawn and paid in the manner to be specified by the administrative Ministry of the public sector undertaking. '],
['Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. In the case of a Government servant who has exercised option (b), family shall be eligible for pensionary benefits on what basis?','The pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation','combined service rendered in both the Government and the public sector undertaking in equal proportion.','combined service rendered in both the Government and the public sector undertaking in accordance with the calculation formula decided by Central Govt.','None of the above','combined service rendered in both the Government and the public sector undertaking in accordance with the calculation formula decided by Central Govt.','Rule 37(12): A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a public sector undertaking shall be entitled to exercise option either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity from the Government for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45; or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that public sector undertaking for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(14) A Government servant who has exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12) and his family shall be eligible for pensionary benefits (including commutation of pension, gratuity, family pension or extra-ordinary pension), on the basis of combined service rendered by the employee in the Government and in the public sector undertaking in accordance with the formula for calculation of such pensionary benefits as may be in force in the Central Government at the time of his retirement from the public sector undertaking or his death.'],
['If a Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a PSU chooses to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that PSU, what pensionary benefits is the Government servant and his family eligible for?','Pension and gratuity.','Commutation of pension, gratuity, family pension or extra-ordinary pension','Only (a)','Both (a) and (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 37(12): A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a public sector undertaking shall be entitled to exercise option either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity, as the case may be, and retirement gratuity from the Government for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45; or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that public sector undertaking for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(14) A Government servant who has exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12) and his family shall be eligible for pensionary benefits (including commutation of pension, gratuity, family pension or extra-ordinary pension), on the basis of combined service rendered by the employee in the Government and in the public sector undertaking in accordance with the formula for calculation of such pensionary benefits as may be in force in the Central Government at the time of his retirement from the public sector undertaking or his death.'],
['On retirement or death of an employee absorbed in PSU and who has exercised option to count service rendered in the Central Govt. in the PSU, the amount of pension or family pension shall be calculated in the same manner as calculated in the case of a:','Central government servant retiring or dying, on the same day','State government servant retiring or dying, on the same day.','Public sector undertaking employee retiring or dying, on the same day','As per the extant guidelines of D/o Public Enterprises','Central government servant retiring or dying, on the same day','Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(15): pensionary benefits for absorbed employees who opt to count their service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU. Upon retirement or death, their pension or family pension shall be calculated in the same manner as a Central Government servant. Emoluments will be based on the pay drawn in the PSU as per Industrial Dearness Allowance pattern. \nRule 37(16): In addition to pension or family pension, the employee shall also be eligible for dearness relief.'],
['Which of the following is NOT correct with regard to a Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of a PSU and chooses to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that PSU? \n1. Upon retirement or death, their pension or family pension shall be calculated in the same manner as a Central Government servant retiring or dying, on the same day. \n2. Emoluments for this purpose will be based on the pay drawn in the PSU as per Industrial Dearness Allowance pattern. \n3. The employee shall also be eligible for dearness relief as per Industrial Dearness Allowance pattern in addition to pension.','1 and 2 only','1 and 3 only','2 and 3 only','All of the above','All of the above','Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(15): pensionary benefits for absorbed employees who opt to count their service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU. Upon retirement or death, their pension or family pension shall be calculated in the same manner as a Central Government servant. Emoluments will be based on the pay drawn in the PSU as per Industrial Dearness Allowance pattern. \nRule 37(16): In addition to pension or family pension, the employee shall also be eligible for dearness relief.'],
['After how many years of qualifying service with the Government and the PSU taken together can a permanent or a temporary Government servant who has been absorbed in the PUS and exercised option to count service rendered in Central Govt. seek voluntary retirement?','5 years','10 years','20 years with minimum of 10 years spent under Central Govt.','25 years or on attaining the age of 55 years whichever is earlier','10 years','Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(17): A permanent Government servant absorbed in a public sector undertaking or a temporary Government servant, who has been confirmed in the public sector undertaking after absorption and has exercised the option to count his service rendered to Central Govt., can seek voluntary retirement after completing ten years of qualifying service with the Government and the public sector undertaking combined. If such a person opts for voluntary retirement, they will be eligible for pensionary benefits as per these rules.'],
['The Central Government creates a Pension Fund in the form of a trust for payment of pension to Govt Servant on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a PSU. Who shall be the Chairperson of the Board of Trustees of this Pension Fund?','The Secretary of the Ministry of Labour and Employment','The Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the PSU','The Secretary of the Department of Public Enterprises','The Secretary of the Department of Pension and Pensioner\'s welfare','The Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the PSU','Rule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. \nRule 37(19)(a) The Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the public sector undertaking shall be the Chairperson of the Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund. (b) The Board of Trustees shall include representatives of the Department of Expenditure, Department of Pension and Pensioner\'s welfare, Ministry of Labour and Employment, concerned public sector undertaking, employees of the concerned public sector undertaking and experts in the relevant field to be nominated by the Central Government.'],
['A Pension Fund in the form of a trust is created by the Central Government to pay pensions to Government servants who are absorbed into a PSU due to the conversion of a Government Department. Who of the following are included in the Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund?','Representatives of D/o Expenditure, Pension and Pensioner\'s Welfare and Labour & Employment','Representatives of concerned public sector undertaking, employees of the concerned public sector undertaking','Experts in the relevant field to be nominated by the Central Government.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. \nRule 37(19)(a) The Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the public sector undertaking shall be the Chairperson of the Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund. (b) The Board of Trustees shall include representatives of the Department of Expenditure, Department of Pension and Pensioner\'s welfare, Ministry of Labour and Employment, concerned public sector undertaking, employees of the concerned public sector undertaking and experts in the relevant field to be nominated by the Central Government.'],
['A Pension Fund in the form of a trust is created by the Central Government to pay pensions to Government servants who are absorbed into a PSU due to the conversion of a Government Department. In this context, which of the option is correct?','The Government, on its own, determines the procedure and manner in which pensionary benefits are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund.','The Board of Trustees determines the procedure and manner in which pensionary benefits are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund.','The Government determines the procedure and manner in which pensionary benefits are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund based on the recommendation of Board of Trustees.','The D/o Public Enterprises has laid the clear guidelines in this regard. ','The Government determines the procedure and manner in which pensionary benefits are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund based on the recommendation of Board of Trustees.','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(20): The procedure and the manner in which pensionary benefits to the employees, who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund shall be determined by the Government on the recommendation of the Board of Trustees. \nRule 37(21)(a) The Government shall discharge its pensionary liability in respect of employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), by paying in lump sum as a one time payment to the Pension Fund. (b) The pensionary liability shall comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the Government servant in the public sector undertaking. (c) Lump sum amount of the pension shall be determined with reference to Commutation Table laid down in Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. \nRule 37(22) The manner of sharing the financial liability on account of payment of pensionary benefits by the public sector undertaking to the employees who have exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (12), shall be determined by the Government.'],
['A Pension Fund in the form of a trust is created by the Central Government to pay pensions to Government servants who are absorbed into a PSU due to the conversion of a Government Department. How is the pensionary liability of the Central Government discharged in respect of employees who have exercised option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that PSU for pension and gratuity?','By paying in monthly instalments to the Pension Fund','By paying in lump sum as a one-time payment to the Pension Fund','By paying directly to the concerned employee','By paying to the public sector undertaking for further disbursement','By paying in lump sum as a one-time payment to the Pension Fund','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(20): The procedure and the manner in which pensionary benefits to the employees, who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund shall be determined by the Government on the recommendation of the Board of Trustees. \nRule 37(21)(a) The Government shall discharge its pensionary liability in respect of employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), by paying in lump sum as a one time payment to the Pension Fund. (b) The pensionary liability shall comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the Government servant in the public sector undertaking. (c) Lump sum amount of the pension shall be determined with reference to Commutation Table laid down in Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. \nRule 37(22) The manner of sharing the financial liability on account of payment of pensionary benefits by the public sector undertaking to the employees who have exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (12), shall be determined by the Government.'],
['Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. The payment of pension to absorbed employees is disbursed through Pension Fund which is managed by the Board of Trustees established by the Central Govt. In this context, which of the following is correct? ','The government discharges its pensionary liability for employees who have opted to receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government by paying a lump sum amount as a one-time payment to the Pension Fund.','This lump sum amount will comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the government servant in the public sector undertaking. ','The Lumpsum amount of pension will be determined by the Board of Trustees instituted. ','The manner of sharing the financial liability on account of payment of pensionary benefits by the public sector undertaking to the employees who have exercised option to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity.','This lump sum amount will comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the government servant in the public sector undertaking. ','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(20): The procedure and the manner in which pensionary benefits to the employees, who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund shall be determined by the Government on the recommendation of the Board of Trustees. \nRule 37(21)(a) The Government shall discharge its pensionary liability in respect of employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), by paying in lump sum as a one time payment to the Pension Fund. (b) The pensionary liability shall comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the Government servant in the public sector undertaking. (c) Lump sum amount of the pension shall be determined with reference to Commutation Table laid down in Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. \nRule 37(22) The manner of sharing the financial liability on account of payment of pensionary benefits by the public sector undertaking to the employees who have exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (12), shall be determined by the Government.'],
['The Government shall discharge its pensionary liability in respect of employees who are absorbed into a PSU due to the conversion of a Government Department and have exercised the option to count their service rendered to the Central Govt. This pensionary liability comprises: ','The capitalised value of pension','The retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the government servant in the PSU.','The capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the government servant in the PSU. ','None of the above','The capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the government servant in the PSU. ','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(20): The procedure and the manner in which pensionary benefits to the employees, who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund shall be determined by the Government on the recommendation of the Board of Trustees. \nRule 37(21)(a) The Government shall discharge its pensionary liability in respect of employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), by paying in lump sum as a one time payment to the Pension Fund. (b) The pensionary liability shall comprise the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered till the date of absorption of the Government servant in the public sector undertaking. (c) Lump sum amount of the pension shall be determined with reference to Commutation Table laid down in Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. \nRule 37(22) The manner of sharing the financial liability on account of payment of pensionary benefits by the public sector undertaking to the employees who have exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (12), shall be determined by the Government.'],
['Which of the following is the responsibility of the PSU (created on conversion of a Govt. Department) for employees who have exercised option to count their service rendered under the Central Govt. under the PSU for retirement/gratuity?','To make contributions to the Pension Fund for their entire service period (including that under Central Govt).','To make contributions to the Pension Fund for the period of service rendered by the employee in the undertaking.','To establish a separate contingency fund to meet its pensionary obligations','To pay pensionary benefits directly to the employee.','To make contributions to the Pension Fund for the period of service rendered by the employee in the undertaking.','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(23) In respect of the employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), the public sector undertaking shall make pensionary contribution to the Pension Fund for the period of service to be rendered by the concerned employees under that undertaking at the rates as may be determined by the Board of Trustees so that the Pension Fund shall be self-supporting. \nRule 37(24) If, for any financial or operational reason, the Trust is unable to discharge its liabilities fully from the Pension Fund and the public sector undertaking is also not in a position to meet the shortfall, the Government, through the administrative Ministry for the public sector undertaking, shall be liable to meet such expenditure and such expenditure shall be debited to either the Fund or to the public sector undertaking. \nRule 37(25) Payments of pensionary benefits of the pensioners of a Government Department who retired from that Department before the date of its conversion into a Public Sector Undertaking shall continue to be the responsibility of the Government and the mechanism for sharing its liabilities on this account shall be determined by the Government.'],
['The PSU (formed on conversion of a Govt. Department) shall make pensionary contributions to the Pension Fund for the employees who have exercised option to count their service rendered to Central Govt under the PSU for retirement and gratuity. The rates shall be determined by the _______________ to ensure the self-sufficiency of the Pension Fund.','Administrative Ministry of the PSU','D/o Public Enterprises from time to time','Board of Trustees','D/o Pension and Pensioner\'s Welfare','Board of Trustees','Rule 37(12): Government servants who have been absorbed as an employees of a PSU are entitled to exercise option, they can either (a) receive pension/gratuity from the Government for their service rendered under the Central Government, or (b) count the service rendered under the Central Government in the PSU for pension and gratuity. \nRule 37(23) In respect of the employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (12), the public sector undertaking shall make pensionary contribution to the Pension Fund for the period of service to be rendered by the concerned employees under that undertaking at the rates as may be determined by the Board of Trustees so that the Pension Fund shall be self-supporting. \nRule 37(24) If, for any financial or operational reason, the Trust is unable to discharge its liabilities fully from the Pension Fund and the public sector undertaking is also not in a position to meet the shortfall, the Government, through the administrative Ministry for the public sector undertaking, shall be liable to meet such expenditure and such expenditure shall be debited to either the Fund or to the public sector undertaking. \nRule 37(25) Payments of pensionary benefits of the pensioners of a Government Department who retired from that Department before the date of its conversion into a Public Sector Undertaking shall continue to be the responsibility of the Government and the mechanism for sharing its liabilities on this account shall be determined by the Government.'],
['The Pension Fund in the form of a trust is created by the Central Government to meet the pension obligation to government servants who are absorbed into a Public Sector Undertaking (PSU) on the conversion of a Government Department. Which entity is liable to meet the expenditure in case of a shortfall in the Pension Fund?','The Public Sector Undertaking','The Board of Trustees','The Government, through the administrative Ministry for the public sector undertaking.','None of the above','The Government, through the administrative Ministry for the public sector undertaking.','Rule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. \nRule 37(24) If, for any financial or operational reason, the Trust is unable to discharge its liabilities fully from the Pension Fund and the public sector undertaking is also not in a position to meet the shortfall, the Government, through the administrative Ministry for the public sector undertaking, shall be liable to meet such expenditure and such expenditure shall be debited to either the Fund or to the public sector undertaking.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding pensionary benefits of the pensioners of a Government Department who retired before its conversion into a PSU?','The PSU will be responsible for the pension payments','The Government will be responsible for the pension payments','The pension payments will be shared between the PSU and the Government','The pension payments will be discontinued after the conversion','The Government will be responsible for the pension payments','Rule 37(25) Payments of pensionary benefits of the pensioners of a Government Department who retired from that Department before the date of its conversion into a Public Sector Undertaking shall continue to be the responsibility of the Government and the mechanism for sharing its liabilities on this account shall be determined by the Government.'],
['The Pension Fund in the form of a trust created by the Central Government to meet the pension obligation to government servants who are absorbed into a Public Sector Undertaking (PSU) on the conversion of a Government Department. However, this is not applicable to which of the following PSU?','Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited','Videsh Sanchar Nigam Limited','Telecommunications Consultants (India) Limited','None of the above','Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited','\nRule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. The Rule 37(18) to (25) are not applicable for the conversion of Telecom Services and Telecom Operations Departments into Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited.\n The summary of Rule 37(26) to (28) is as under:\n In this case, the Government will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits including family pension. The Government will specify the arrangements and the manner including the rate of pensionary contributions to be made by Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited to the Government, and the manner in which financial liabilities on this account shall be met. These arrangements will apply to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service for absorption in Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited, but not to the employees directly recruited by these companies who will have their own pension schemes.'],
['Which of the following is true regarding the conversion of Telecom Services and Telecom Operations Departments into Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited?','The companies will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service.','The Government will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits including family pension to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service.','The companies will be responsible for devising their own pension schemes and making arrangements for funding and disbursing the pensionary benefits.','The Pensionary benefits shall be disbursed through the Pension Fund established in the form of a Trust in accordance with Rule 37(18) of CCS Pension Rules, 2021.','The Government will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits including family pension to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service.','Rule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. The Rule 37(18) to (25) are not applicable for the conversion of Telecom Services and Telecom Operations Departments into Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited.\n The summary of Rule 37(26) to (28) is as under:\n In this case, the Government will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits including family pension. The Government will specify the arrangements and the manner including the rate of pensionary contributions to be made by Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited to the Government, and the manner in which financial liabilities on this account shall be met. These arrangements will apply to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service for absorption in Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited, but not to the employees directly recruited by these companies who will have their own pension schemes.'],
['Which of the following is correct in respect of the conversion of Telecom Services and Telecom Operations Departments into BSNL and MTNL?','The Government will specify the arrangements and the manner including the rate of pensionary contributions to be made by BSNL and MTNL to the Government, and the manner in which financial liabilities on this account shall be met.','These arrangements will apply to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service for absorption in BSNL and MTNL, including the employees directly recruited by these companies.','The Pensionary benefits shall be disbursed through the Pension Fund established in the form of a Trust in accordance with Rule 37(18) of CCS Pension Rules, 2021.','None of the above','The Government will specify the arrangements and the manner including the rate of pensionary contributions to be made by BSNL and MTNL to the Government, and the manner in which financial liabilities on this account shall be met.','Rule 37(18) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. The Rule 37(18) to (25) are not applicable for the conversion of Telecom Services and Telecom Operations Departments into Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited.\n The summary of Rule 37(26) to (28) is as under:\n In this case, the Government will be responsible for paying pensionary benefits including family pension. The Government will specify the arrangements and the manner including the rate of pensionary contributions to be made by Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited to the Government, and the manner in which financial liabilities on this account shall be met. These arrangements will apply to the existing pensioners and the employees who are deemed to have retired from the Government service for absorption in Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited and Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited, but not to the employees directly recruited by these companies who will have their own pension schemes.'],
['What happens to the provident fund balance of absorbed employees upon conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking?','It is refunded to the Govt. Servant','It is transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the new undertaking','It remains with the Government and transferred to the Pension Fund established to pay the pensionary benefits. ','None of the above','It is transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the new undertaking','Rule 37(29): Upon conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking, the following shall take place: \n(a) The balance of provident fund and earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the absorbed employees shall be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the public sector undertaking with their consent. \n(b) The dismissal or removal from service of any employee after absorption in the public sector undertaking for any subsequent misconduct shall not result in forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government. In the event of dismissal, removal, or retrenchment, the decisions of the undertaking shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the undertaking.'],
['What happens to the EL and HPL balance of absorbed employees upon conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking?','Cash equivalent of the EL and HPL is paid to the Govt. servant subject to maximum leave of 300 days','It is transferred to such undertaking','The Leave Rules of the new PSU applies in such cases which are to be framed by the PSU itself.','None of the above','It is transferred to such undertaking','Rule 37(29): Upon conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking, the following shall take place: \n(a) The balance of provident fund and earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the absorbed employees shall be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the public sector undertaking with their consent. \n(b) The dismissal or removal from service of any employee after absorption in the public sector undertaking for any subsequent misconduct shall not result in forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government. In the event of dismissal, removal, or retrenchment, the decisions of the undertaking shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the undertaking.'],
['Which of the following is correct with regard to the conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking?','Dismissal or removal from service of an employee after their absorption in a public sector undertaking for subsequent misconduct will not lead to forfeiture of retirement benefits for the service rendered under the government.','In case of dismissal, removal or retrenchment of an absorbed employee, the decisions of the undertaking will be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the undertaking.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 37(29): Upon conversion of a Government Department into a public sector undertaking, the following shall take place: \n(a) The balance of provident fund and earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the absorbed employees shall be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the public sector undertaking with their consent. \n(b) The dismissal or removal from service of any employee after absorption in the public sector undertaking for any subsequent misconduct shall not result in forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government. In the event of dismissal, removal, or retrenchment, the decisions of the undertaking shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the undertaking.'],
['Following the conversion of a Government Department into a PSU, if the government disinvests more than 51% of its equity in a public sector undertaking, it must specify safeguards to protect the interests of ____________.','All Employees','Only Absorbed Employees','as specified by the D/o Public Enterprises','None of the above','Only Absorbed Employees','Rule 37 relatest to the conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking. \nRule 37(30): If the government disinvests more than 51% of its equity in a public sector undertaking, it must specify safeguards to protect the interests of absorbed employees. \nRule 37(31): These safeguards may include the option for voluntary retirement or continued service in the undertaking, retirement benefits on terms applicable to government or public sector undertaking employees, and assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in the period of qualifying service as determined by the government.'],
['If the government disinvests more than 51% of its equity in a public sector undertaking (formed upon conversion of a Govt. Department), it must specify safeguards to protect the interests of absorbed employees. These safeguards may include: ','Option for voluntary retirement or continued service in the undertaking','Retirement benefits on terms applicable to government or public sector undertaking employees','Assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in the period of qualifying service as determined by the government.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 37 relatest to the conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Public Sector Undertaking. \nRule 37(30): If the government disinvests more than 51% of its equity in a public sector undertaking, it must specify safeguards to protect the interests of absorbed employees. \nRule 37(31): These safeguards may include the option for voluntary retirement or continued service in the undertaking, retirement benefits on terms applicable to government or public sector undertaking employees, and assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in the period of qualifying service as determined by the government.'],
['What happens to the government servants of a department when it is converted into an autonomous body?','They will be transferred en-masse to the autonomous body on deemed deputation on foreign service terms.','They will be given a option to stay or leave the job.','They will be transferred en-masse to the autonomous body on deemed deputation on foreign service terms with Deputation allowance.','None of the above','They will be transferred en-masse to the autonomous body on deemed deputation on foreign service terms.','Rule 38. Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- \nRule 38(1) On conversion of a department of the Central Government into an autonomous body, all Government servants of that Department shall be transferred en-masse to that autonomous body on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance till such time as they get absorbed in the said body and such transferred Government servants shall be absorbed in the autonomous body with effect from such date as may be notified by the Government.'],
['Within what time frame should the autonomous body frame its rules and regulations after the conversion from a department?','Within 1 year','Within 2 years','Within 3 years','Within 5 years','Within 5 years','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- \nSummary of Rule 38(1) to Rule 38(3): \nwhen a Central Government department is converted into an autonomous body, all government employees from that department will be transferred to the autonomous body on deemed deputation. The employees will not receive any deputation allowance until they are absorbed into the autonomous body. The autonomous body will have to create its own rules and regulations within five years, and after that, all employees on deemed deputation will have to choose between going back to the government or staying with the autonomous body. They will be given a period of three months to make their decision. Every transferred Government servant must exercise the option specified by the government within the prescribed time limit. If an employee fails to exercise any option within the time limit, they will be deemed to have chosen permanent absorption in the autonomous body.'],
['Which of the following is correct with regard to the absorption of Govt. Employee consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body?','The permanent absorption of the Government servants as employees of the autonomous body shall take effect from the date on which they excercise their option. ','When Government servants are absorbed permanently as employees of an autonomous body, they shall cease to be Government servants and they shall be deemed to have retired from Government service.','Employees who choose to revert to Government service will be repatriated to the Government within six months from the date of exercise of the option.','None of the above','When Government servants are absorbed permanently as employees of an autonomous body, they shall cease to be Government servants and they shall be deemed to have retired from Government service.','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- \nSummary of Rule 38(1) to Rule 38(3): \nwhen a Central Government department is converted into an autonomous body, all government employees from that department will be transferred to the autonomous body on deemed deputation. The employees will not receive any deputation allowance until they are absorbed into the autonomous body. The autonomous body will have to create its own rules and regulations within five years, and after that, all employees on deemed deputation will have to choose between going back to the government or staying with the autonomous body. They will be given a period of three months to make their decision. Every transferred Government servant must exercise the option specified by the government within the prescribed time limit. If an employee fails to exercise any option within the time limit, they will be deemed to have chosen permanent absorption in the autonomous body.'],
['Which of the following is correct with regard to the absorption of Govt. Employee consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body? \n1. Government servants are absorbed permanently as employees of an autonomous body, they will cease to be Government servants and the posts that they held in the Government will stand abolished. \n2. Employees who choose to revert to Government service will be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government.','1 only','2 only','Both 1 and 2','Neither 1 nor 2','Both 1 and 2','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- \nRule 38(4) The permanent absorption of the Government servants as employees of the autonomous body shall take effect from the date on which their options are accepted by the Government and on and from the date of such acceptance, such employees shall cease to be Government servants and they shall be deemed to have retired from Government service. \Rule 38(5) In case of absorption of Government servants in the autonomous body, the posts which they were holding in the Government before such absorption shall stand abolished. \nRule 38(6) The employees who opt to revert to Government service shall be repatriated to the Government within two years from the date of exercise of the option and shall be redeployed through the surplus cell of the Government.'],
['When a Central Government department is converted into an autonomous body, all government employees from that department will be transferred to the autonomous body and will have to choose between going back to the government or staying with the autonomous body. Keeping this in background, which of the following is NOT correct?','If the employees choosess to revert, the period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government, the employee shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance.','If an employee retires or dies during the period of deemed deputation, the pay which he/she would have drawn under the Central Government had he/she not been on deemed deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government.','When an employee retires or dies during the period of deemed deputation, the pensionary benefits in respect of such employee shall be drawn and paid in the manner specified by the administrative Ministry of the autonomous body.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- When a Central Government department is converted into an autonomous body, all government employees from that department will be transferred to the autonomous body on deemed deputation. The employees will not receive any deputation allowance until they are absorbed into the autonomous body. The autonomous body will have to create its own rules and regulations within five years, and after that, all employees on deemed deputation will have to choose between going back to the government or staying with the autonomous body. \nRule 38(7) The period between the date of option and the date of reversion to the Government shall continue to be on deemed deputation on terms of foreign service without any deputation allowance. \nRule 38(8) Where an employee retires or dies during the period of such deemed deputation, the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government. \nRule 38(9) The pensionary benefits in respect of such employee shall be drawn and paid in the manner to be specified by the administrative Ministry of the autonomous body.'],
['What is the option available to a Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of an autonomous body (formed after conversion of a Govt. Department) ?','They can choose to receive pension or gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government.','They can count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension and gratuity.','Either (a) or (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Either (a) or (b)','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body- When a Central Government department is converted into an autonomous body, all government employees from that department will be transferred to the autonomous body on deemed deputation. The employees will not receive any deputation allowance until they are absorbed into the autonomous body. The autonomous body will have to create its own rules and regulations within five years, and after that, all employees on deemed deputation will have to choose between going back to the government or staying with the autonomous body. \nRule 38(11) A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of the autonomous body shall be entitled to exercise option either,- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity, as the case may be, for the service rendered under the Central Government in accordance with rule 44 and rule 45 of these rules; or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension and gratuity.'],
['A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of the autonomous body (established by the conversion of a Govt. Department) can either choose (a) to receive a pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or (b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. Which of the following statements is true about the pensionary benefits of a government servant who has exercised option (a) given above?','The pensionary benefits shall be calculated based on the emoluments drawn by the employee in the autonomous body.','he pensionary benefits shall be calculated based on the emoluments the employee would have drawn under the Central Government had they not been on deemed deputation.','The pensionary benefits shall be paid by the autonomous body.','The administrative Ministry of the autonomous body shall have no role in the drawing and payment of pensionary benefits.','he pensionary benefits shall be calculated based on the emoluments the employee would have drawn under the Central Government had they not been on deemed deputation.','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity.\nRule 38(12) In the case of a Government servant who has exercised option under clause (a) of sub-rule (11), the pay which he would have drawn under the Central Government had he not been on deemed deputation shall be treated as emoluments for calculating the pensionary benefits to be paid by the Government. \nRule 38(13) The pensionary benefits in respect of such employee shall be drawn and paid in the manner to be specified by the administrative Ministry of the autonomous body.'],
['Which of the following is accurate with regard to pensionary benefits to Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of the autonomous body (established by the conversion of a Govt. Department) and chose to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension and gratuity?','The employee will be eligible for pensionary benefits based on the combined service rendered in the Government and the autonomous body.','The Govt. servant will be eligible for Pension and Retirement Gratuity only.','Both (a) and (b)','Neitther (a) nor (b)','The employee will be eligible for pensionary benefits based on the combined service rendered in the Government and the autonomous body.','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. \nRule 38(14) A Government servant who has exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (11) and his family shall be eligible for pensionary benefits (including commutation of pension, gratuity, family pension or extra-ordinary pension), on the basis of combined service rendered by the employee in the Government and in the autonomous body in accordance with the formula for calculation of such pensionary benefits as may be in force at the time of his retirement from the autonomous body or his death.'],
['A Government servant who has been absorbed as an employee of the autonomous body (formed by the conversion of a Govt. Department) and has opted to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension and gratuity, on retirement or death shall be eligible for:','Dearness relief as per central dearness allowance pattern.','Commutation of pension, Gratuity, Family pension or extra-ordinary pension','Both (a) and (b)','Neitther (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. \nRule 38(14) A Government servant who has exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (11) and his family shall be eligible for pensionary benefits (including commutation of pension, gratuity, family pension or extra-ordinary pension), on the basis of combined service rendered by the employee in the Government and in the autonomous body in accordance with the formula for calculation of such pensionary benefits as may be in force at the time of his retirement from the autonomous body or his death. \nRule 38(15) In addition to pension or family pension, as the case may be, the absorbed employees who opt for pension on the basis of combined service shall also be eligible to dearness relief as per central dearness allowance pattern.'],
['With regard to the payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body, which of the following is NOT correct?','The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund.','The Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund will be chaired by the Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the autonomous body.','The government will determine the procedure and manner in which pensionary benefits are to be sanctioned and disbursed to employees, who chose to count the service rendered under the Central Govt. under that Body for pension/gratuity, from the Pension Fund, based on the recommendations of the Board of Trustees.','The Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund will include representative from various Govt. Department including D/o Public Enterprises.','The Board of Trustees of the Pension Fund will include representative from various Govt. Department including D/o Public Enterprises.','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. \nRule 38(16) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. \nRule 38(17) The Secretary of the administrative Ministry of the autonomous body shall be the Chairperson of the Board of Trustees which shall include representatives of the Department of Expenditure, Department of Pension and and Pensioner\'s welfare, Ministry of Labour and Employment, concerned autonomous body, employees of the concerned autonomous body and experts in the relevant field to be nominated by the Central Government. \nRule 38(18) The procedure and the manner in which pensionary benefits to the employees, who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (11), are to be sanctioned and disbursed from the Pension Fund shall be determined by the Government on the recommendation of the Board of Trustees. '],
['When a Government servant is absorbed as an employee of an autonomous body that was created by the conversion of a Government Department, they have two options. The first is to receive a pension and retirement gratuity for the service they rendered under the Central Government. The second option is to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. In this context, which of the following is correct?','The Government will pay its pensionary liability for employees who opted to receive a pension and retirement gratuity for the service they rendered under the Central Government in a lump sum to the Pension Fund.','The Government will determine the manner of sharing the financial liability by the autonomous body in respect of employees who opted to count the service rendered under the Central Government in that body for pension and gratuity.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. Summary of Rule 38(19) to 38(22): The Government will pay its pensionary liability for employees who opted for clause (b) of sub-rule (11) in a lump sum to the Pension Fund. The pensionary liability includes the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered until the date of absorption in the autonomous body. The lump sum amount of the pension will be determined with reference to the Commutation Table in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. The Government will determine the manner of sharing the financial liability for employees who opted for clause (a) of sub-rule (11) by the autonomous body.'],
['Which of the following is correct with regard to pensionary liabilities when a Government servant is absorbed as an employee of an autonomous body that was created by the conversion of a Government Department and opted to count service rendered to the Central Govt. under that body for Pension/Gratuity?','The pensionary liability includes the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered until the date of absorption in the autonomous body.','The lump sum amount of the pension will be determined with reference to the Commutation Table in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. Summary of Rule 38(19) to 38(22): The Government will pay its pensionary liability for employees who opted for clause (b) of sub-rule (11) in a lump sum to the Pension Fund. The pensionary liability includes the capitalised value of pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered until the date of absorption in the autonomous body. The lump sum amount of the pension will be determined with reference to the Commutation Table in the Central Civil Services (Commutation of Pension) Rules, 1981. The Government will determine the manner of sharing the financial liability for employees who opted for clause (a) of sub-rule (11) by the autonomous body.'],
['The payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body is disbursed through Pension Fund created in the form of a trust. Which of the following statement(s) relating to Pension Fund is true?','In case the Trust is unable to fully discharge its liabilities from the Pension Fund and the autonomous body is also unable to meet the shortfall, the Government through the Administrative Ministry will be liable to meet such expenditure.','Such expenditure shall be debited to either the Fund or to the autonomous body, as the case may be.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','Rule 38- Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body. \nRule 38(16) The Central Government shall create a Pension Fund in the form of a trust and the pensionary benefits of absorbed employees shall be paid out of such Pension Fund. \nRule 38(24) If, for any financial or operational reason, the Trust is unable to discharge its liabilities fully from the Pension Fund and the autonomous body is also not in a position to meet the shortfall, the Government, through the administrative Ministry for the autonomous body, shall be liable to meet such expenditure and such expenditure shall be debited to either the Fund or to the autonomous body, as the case may be.'],
['Employees who opt to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity for will have their pensionary contribution made by the autonomous body to the Pension Fund for the period of service ______________ at rates determined by the Board of Trustees, ensuring the Pension Fund remains self-supporting.','rendered under the Central Govt.','rendered under the autonomous body','rendered under the Central Govt and Autonomous Body combined','None of the above','rendered under the autonomous body','Rule 38(11) The absorbed Government servant can choose either- \n(a) to receive pension or service gratuity and retirement gratuity for the service rendered under the Central Government or \n(b) to count the service rendered under the Central Government in the autonomous body for pension and gratuity. \nRule 38(23) In respect of the employees who have exercised option under clause (b) of sub-rule (11), the autonomous body shall make pensionary contribution to the Pension Fund for the period of service to be rendered by the concerned employees under that body at the rates as may be determined by the Board of Trustees so that the Pension Fund shall be self-supporting.'],
['The payment of pensionary benefits to pensioners of a Government Department who retired before its conversion into an autonomous body will remain the responsibility of the Government, and the sharing mechanism for its liabilities will be determined by the ______________.','Government','Autonomous Body','The Board of Trustees','By the mutual agreement between the Govt. and the Autonomous Body','Government','Rule 38. Conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body. \nRule 38(25): Payments of pensionary benefits of the pensioners of a Government Department who retired from that Department before the date of its conversion into an autonomous body shall continue to be the responsibility of the Government and the mechanism for sharing its liabilities on this account shall be determined by the Government. '],
[' In case of conversion of a Government Department into an autonomous body, what happens to the balance of provident fund standing at the credit of the absorbed employees on the date of their absorption in the autonomous body?','It is paid out to the Employee','It is transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the autonomous body.','It is transferred under the Pension Fund managed by Board of Trustees','The Govt. retains it and disburses to the Employee on retirement or death. ','It is transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in the autonomous body.','Rule 38 (26) In case of conversion of a Government Department into an autonomous body- \n(a) the balance of provident fund standing at the credit of the absorbed employees on the date of their absorption in the autonomous body shall, with the consent of such body, be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in such body; \n(b) earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the employees on the date of absorption shall stand transferred to such body; \n(c) the dismissal or removal from service of the autonomous body of any employee after his absorption in such body for any subsequent misconduct shall not amount to forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government and in the event of his dismissal or removal or retrenchment the decisions of the body shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body.'],
[' What happens to earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the employees on the date of absorption in the autonomous body, in case of conversion of a Government Department into an autonomous body?','It stands transferred to the Autonmous Body','The cash equivalent of the EL and HPL is paid out to the employee subject to the maximum 300 days','The Cash equivalent amount is transferred under the Pension Fund for disbursement at the time of retirement or death.','None of the above','It stands transferred to the Autonmous Body','Rule 38 (26) In case of conversion of a Government Department into an autonomous body- \n(a) the balance of provident fund standing at the credit of the absorbed employees on the date of their absorption in the autonomous body shall, with the consent of such body, be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in such body; \n(b) earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the employees on the date of absorption shall stand transferred to such body; \n(c) the dismissal or removal from service of the autonomous body of any employee after his absorption in such body for any subsequent misconduct shall not amount to forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government and in the event of his dismissal or removal or retrenchment the decisions of the body shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body.'],
['What happens to retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government in case an employee of the autonomous body is dismissed or removed from service for any subsequent misconduct?','Retirement benefits are not forfeited and in event of his dismissal or removal or retrenchment, the decisions of the autonomous body will be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body','Retirement benefits are forfeited but it will be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body.','Retirement Benefits are paid on provisional basis until the same is reviewed by the concerned Ministry.','None of the above','Retirement benefits are not forfeited and in event of his dismissal or removal or retrenchment, the decisions of the autonomous body will be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body','Rule 38 (26) In case of conversion of a Government Department into an autonomous body- \n(a) the balance of provident fund standing at the credit of the absorbed employees on the date of their absorption in the autonomous body shall, with the consent of such body, be transferred to the new Provident Fund Account of the employees in such body; \n(b) earned leave and half pay leave at the credit of the employees on the date of absorption shall stand transferred to such body; \n(c) the dismissal or removal from service of the autonomous body of any employee after his absorption in such body for any subsequent misconduct shall not amount to forfeiture of the retirement benefits for the service rendered under the Government and in the event of his dismissal or removal or retrenchment the decisions of the body shall be subject to review by the Ministry administratively concerned with the body.'],
['What does the Government need to do if it disinvests its equity in an autonomous body to the extent of fifty-one per cent or more?','The Government need not take any action.','The Government needs to specify adequate safeguards for protecting the interest of the absorbed employees of such autonomous body','The Government needs to transfer the absorbed employees to another autonomous body.','The Government gives second option to the absorbed employees to revert back under the Central Govt.','The Government needs to specify adequate safeguards for protecting the interest of the absorbed employees of such autonomous body','Rule 38 (27): In case the Government disinvests its equity in any autonomous body to the extent of fifty-one per cent or more, it shall specify adequate safeguards for protecting the interest of the absorbed employees of such autonomous body. \nRule 38(28): The safeguards specified under sub-rule (27) shall include option for voluntary retirement or continued service in the body, as the case may be, or voluntary retirement benefits on terms applicable to Government employees or employees of the autonomous body as per option of the employees, assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in period of qualifying service, as may be decided by the Government.'],
['The Government needs to specify adequate safeguards for protecting the interest of the absorbed employees of such autonomous body if it disinvests its equity in that body to the extent of fifty-one per cent or more. These safeguards may include: ','Voluntary retirement benefits on terms applicable to Government employees or employees of the autonomous body as per option of the employees.','Option for voluntary retirement or continued service, assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in period of qualifying service.','Assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in period of qualifying service.','All of the above','All of the above','Rule 38 (27): In case the Government disinvests its equity in any autonomous body to the extent of fifty-one per cent or more, it shall specify adequate safeguards for protecting the interest of the absorbed employees of such autonomous body. \nRule 38(28): The safeguards specified under sub-rule (27) shall include option for voluntary retirement or continued service in the body, as the case may be, or voluntary retirement benefits on terms applicable to Government employees or employees of the autonomous body as per option of the employees, assured payment of earned pensionary benefits with relaxation in period of qualifying service, as may be decided by the Government.'],
['Rule 38 of CCS (Pension) Rules, 2021 is related to the conditions for payment of pension on absorption consequent upon conversion of a Government Department into a Central Autonomous Body. \nWhich group of employees are excluded from the applicability of this rule?','Employees of the Central Secretariat Service who are working in Akashvani and Doordarshan and involved in activities that have been transferred to Prasar Bharati under the Prasar Bharati (Broadcasting Corporation of India) Act, 1990.','Members of Indian Information Servic who are working in Akashvani and Doordarshan and involved in activities that have been transferred to Prasar Bharati under the Prasar Bharati (Broadcasting Corporation of India) Act, 1990.','Both (a) and (b)','Neither (a) nor (b)','Both (a) and (b)','\nRule 38(29) Nothing contained in this rule shall be applicable to the officers or employees including members of Indian Information Service, Central Secretariat Service or any other service or to the persons borne on cadres outside Akashvani and Doordarshan, serving in the Akashvani and Doordarshan and engaged in the performance of functions transferred to Prasar Bharati established under Prasar Bharati (Broadcasting Corporation of India) Act, 1990.'],

];